<li id="cite_note-sastri116-33"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-sastri116_33-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-sastri116_33-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="../K.A._Nilakanta_Sastri" title="K.A. Nilakanta Sastri" class="mw-redirect">K.A. Nilakanta Sastri</a>, <i>A History of South India</i>, p 116</span></li>
<li id="cite_note-34"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-34">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="../K.A._Nilakanta_Sastri" title="K.A. Nilakanta Sastri" class="mw-redirect">K.A. Nilakanta Sastri</a>, <i>A History of South India</i>, pp 105–106</span></li>
<li id="cite_note-earlydate-35"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-earlydate_35-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The only evidence for the approximate period of these early kings is the Sangam Literature and the synchronization with the <a href="History_of_Sri_Lanka" title="History of Sri Lanka">history of Sri Lanka</a> as given in the Mahavamsa. <a href="Gajabahu_I" title="Gajabahu I" class="mw-redirect">Gajabahu I</a> who is said to be the contemporary of the Chera <a href="Senguttuvan" title="Senguttuvan" class="mw-redirect">Senguttuvan</a> is determined to belong to the 2nd century. This leads us to date the poems mentioning Senguttuvan and his contemporaries to belong to this period.</span></li>
<li id="cite_note-36"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-36">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="../K.A._Nilakanta_Sastri" title="K.A. Nilakanta Sastri" class="mw-redirect">K.A. Nilakanta Sastri</a>, <i>A History of South India</i>, p 113</span></li>
