<li id="cite_note-learning-120"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-learning_120-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Rajendra Chola I endowed a large college in which more than 280 students learnt from 14 teachers – <a href="../K.A._Nilakanta_Sastri" title="K.A. Nilakanta Sastri" class="mw-redirect">K.A. Nilakanta Sastri</a>, <i>A History of South India</i>, p 293</span></li>
<li id="cite_note-subjects-121"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-subjects_121-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The students studied a number of subjects in these colleges, including philosophy (<i>anvikshiki</i>), <a href="Vedas" title="Vedas">Vedas</a> (<i>trayi</i> – the threefold Vedas of <a href="Rigveda" title="Rigveda">Rigveda</a>, <a href="Yajurveda" title="Yajurveda">Yajurveda</a> and <a href="Samaveda" title="Samaveda">Samaveda</a>. The fourth <a href="Atharvaveda" title="Atharvaveda">Atharvaveda</a> was considered a non-religious text.), economics (<i>vartta</i>), government (<i>dandaniti</i>), grammar, prosody, etymology, astronomy, logic (<i>tarka</i>), medicine (<i>ayurveda</i>), politics (<i>arthasastra</i>) and music. – <a href="../K.A._Nilakanta_Sastri" title="K.A. Nilakanta Sastri" class="mw-redirect">K.A. Nilakanta Sastri</a>, <i>A History of South India</i>, p 292</span></li>
